Summary__c: Along the Zambezi River basin in Southern Africa, vulnerable communities are frequently exposed to natural disasters, particularly flooding and drought.  Since late 2011, the American Red Cross has been working with communities to identify and mitigate common hazards, and implement small-scale resiliency projects such as helping to flood-proof homes, developing flood early warning systems, building latrines and teaching communities how to prepare for and respond to disasters. At the same time, the American Red Cross is strengthening the capacity of national societies through trainings and community contingency planning.  A partnership between the American Red Cross and Red Cross partners in Namibia and Zimbabwe, this project aims to reach more than 14,000 people in these two countries including 6,700 in Namibia and more than 7,500 in Zimbabwe.

Name: Disaster Project - Haiti & Dominican Republic: Cholera-2010
Summary__c:
·         Since October 2010, when the first cholera cases were reported in Haiti in more than 100 years, the cholera caseload in Haiti and the Dominican Republic has increased dramatically.  Cholera has killed more than 8,500 people in Haiti and 454 people in the Dominican Republic since 2010, and more than 650,000 Haitians and 30,000 Dominicans have contracted the disease during this period.
·         In 2012, the governments of Haiti and the Dominican Republic developed ten-year national action plans outlining investments and interventions necessary to eliminate the transmission of cholera by 2022.  Agencies working in support of the respective national plans, including the Red Cross, formed a coalition to coordinate cholera response efforts.
·         In recent years, Red Cross efforts have contributed to a reduction in the number of cholera cases in Haiti and the Dominican Republic.  However, eradication of the disease requires further reducing the number of cholera cases, increasing awareness of beneficial hygiene and sanitation practices, increasing national capacity to detect and control cholera outbreaks, reducing the risk of contamination, and supporting treatment of cholera patients.

Vietnam Floods-2011
Summary__c:
·          According to the Vietnam government’s flood control agency, a total of 140,000 households (approximately 590,000 people) have been affected by the floods.  At least 73 people are dead, more than 91,400 houses are damaged and 24,000 acres of rice paddies destroyed.
·          Government authorities have opened shelters and health stations to support those in need, but food supplies are low and people continue to face difficulties in everyday living.
·          Assessments performed by the Vietnam Red Cross and other agencies indicate that the greatest needs are for food, tarps, blankets, mosquito nets, safe water, hygiene and health promotion activities.
·          According to the Mekong River Commission, floodwaters are forecasted to remain high at least until mid-November.

Name: Bangladesh Floods-2012
Summary__c:
·         While still responding to the heavy rains from earlier this year that caused floods and landslides in ten districts, Bangladesh was struck by a fast moving tropical storm that caused damage to over 27,000 homes in three districts on the coast.
·         Due to the quick onset of the storm, as meteorological agencies weren’t able to give much advanced warning, the fishing community was particularly affected by being caught out on the water.
·         Organizations on the ground in Bangladesh are coordinating response activities with the government and through the Humanitarian Coordination Task Team (HCTT).

Afghanistan Floods-2012
Summary__c:
·         Melting snow and heavy rain have caused flash floods in the Sar-e-Pol and Jawzjan provinces of Afghanistan, damaging property and livelihoods.  
·         Over five thousand homes have been damaged or destroyed, leaving many families unable to find alternative shelter.
·         Water supply systems are inundated and local markets are difficult to access, making shelter, food, water and healthcare the top priorities for the response efforts.

Palestine Gaza Crisis-2012
Summary__c:
·         Starting on November 14, 2012, eight days of fighting across the border between Israel and Gaza resulted in 160 deaths and nearly 1,400 injuries in Gaza.
·         Initial assessments in Gaza indicated that 137 houses were completely destroyed and 294 had been damaged.
·         Airstrikes destroyed infrastructure and displaced approximately 12,000 people.
·         Initial assessments also indicated an immediate need for relief supplies, medical supplies and ambulances.

Name: Kenya Floods-2013
Summary__c:
·         Seasonal rains starting in March 2013 have caused severe flooding and landslides in Kenya, destroying houses, crops and vital infrastructure, forcing affected populations to leave their homes in search of safer areas.
·         Flooding has displaced 10,000 households, caused 39 deaths and destroyed 640 households completely.
·         Rains are forecasted to continue into the month of June and could worsen flooding and cause further displacement and destruction.
·         Immediate needs include search and rescue services, safe shelter, access to water and improved sanitation, health and hygiene education, and grants to enable affected populations to purchase the supplies they need in areas where markets are functioning.

Summary__c: Since the beginning of August, monsoon rains have caused widespread flooding in southern Pakistan and isolated floods and landslides across the north of the country, affecting 5 million people.

Argentina Floods-2013
Summary__c:
·         On April 2, 2013 a severe storm caused heavy flooding in La Plata, the capital of Buenos Aires province in Argentina, bringing eleven inches of rain overnight. This was the highest level of rainfall the area experienced in a 24 hour period since 1980.
·         Flood waters rose to over six feet in some areas causing destruction of homes and disruption to power and clean water supply.
·         The floods affected over 350,000 people, caused 52 deaths and resulted in 3,000 people evacuating to shelters.

Name: Malawi Food Security-2012
Summary__c:
·         As a result of low food production in some districts and an increasing economic crisis, Malawi is facing a critical food shortage, affecting an estimated 1.9 million people.
·         The food shortage is concentrated in central and southern Malawi, affecting approximately 11% of the total population and over 50% of the population in two southern districts, Nsanje and Chikhwawa.
·         Heavy rains and flooding in the spring, followed by prolonged dry spells resulted in poor harvests this fall. The next harvest season is not expected until March 2013. 
·         The current situation is exacerbated by fuel shortages, rising food prices, and rapid inflation which occurred earlier this year.

Name: Sierra Leone Cholera Outbreak-2012
Summary__c:
·         Since the first cases were reported in February, the latest cholera outbreak in Sierra Leone has caused an estimated 217 deaths and affected almost 12,000 people.
·         The rate of new cases has accelerated rapidly since the beginning of August and spread to 10 of the country’s 13 districts.
·         Hospitals and health centres in some districts lack clean water and stable power. The actual number of cholera cases may be higher than what has been reported because cases are often unreported or not treated by proper medical personnel. 
·         There are a number of organizations currently responding in Sierra Leone but the majority are concentrated in the capital of Freetown.

Name: Sahel Food Crisis-2012
Summary__c:
·          More than 11 million people in the Sahel region of West Africa, which includes Burkina Faso, Chad, Mali, Mauritania, Niger and some parts of Senegal, face severe food shortages due to crop failure caused by erratic rainfall and drought.
·          This will worsen the chronic risk of food insecurity and malnutrition many families in the region already face. The Sahel region will run out of food stocks earlier than usual and already high food prices are expected to increase, which will limit families’ ability to purchase additional food at markets.
·          Immediate priority needs are for food assistance, nutritional supplements and agriculture support.
·          In several regions in Chad, Mauritania, Niger and Senegal, child malnutrition rates are already above the emergency threshold of 15 percent. Without immediate action, the situation is predicted to worsen.
·          The population’s ability to obtain food has also been impacted by an increase in crime and insecurity due to armed groups in Chad, Mali, Mauritania and Niger.

Paraguay Drought-2012
Summary__c:
·          A La Niña weather phenomenon has created irregular rain patterns throughout South America, causing a serious drought in Paraguay. The drought has hit southern Paraguay in one of the most important agricultural regions of the country. 
·          The government declared a food security emergency in January. It reports that 8 of the country’s 17 departments are under a serious drought, with agriculture production reduced by 30 to 50 percent.
·          Small farmers and food producers are particularly hard hit; more than 263,800 households are experiencing crop loss and are in need of food. 
·          The most immediate needs for the short term are for safe water, food items and seeds for immediate planting. The drought has limited the movement of food and commercial shipping along rivers due to low water levels and led to a lack of safe water for household use.

Name: Nigeria Floods-2012
Summary__c:
·         Between July and October 2012, the worst flooding Nigeria has experienced in 40 years has affected 7 million people, killed 363, and displaced 2.1 million.  
·         Flooding has affected 33 of Nigeria’s 36 states, with the greatest impact currently in the southern parts of the country. 
·         Flooding has destroyed crops and damaged roads and bridges making transportation of goods to communities extremely difficult. In some flooded areas, food prices have increased by 30 to 70 percent resulting in food insecurity.
§  Displaced people are living with host families or in camps and schools, many of which do not have adequate sanitation facilities and drinking water. This situation is also preventing schools from functioning normally.

Name: DR Congo Population Movement-2013
Summary__c:
·         Since December 2012, refugees escaping violence in the Central African Republic (CAR) have been migrating into Equateur, a province in the north of the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC).
·         According to the UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs, more than 30,000 refugees from CAR are now residing in DRC. The population remains in flux and the numbers could increase due to the overthrow of the CAR government by rebels in March 2013.  
·         Immediate needs include temporary shelter, food, water and reconnecting separated family members. Assessments have also highlighted health, nutrition and protection for the displaced population as additional needs.

Name: Philippines Typhoons-2011
Summary__c: Two typhoons have hit the Philippines within a five-day span. Typhoon Nesat struck September 27 with strong gusts and heavy rains, triggering floods and widespread damage across the entire island of Luzon. Before the country could recover, another less powerful storm, Typhoon Nalgae, struck on October 1, following the same route, adding to flooding and isolating communities.

Name: Bolivia Floods-2012
Summary__c:
·          A La Niña weather phenomenon has created irregular rain patterns throughout South America, causing serious flooding in Bolivia.  Floods have affected virtually all of the country. 
·          More than 13,000 families (or 65,000 people) are affected. The government declared a state of emergency in February. Rains are predicted to continue into April.
·          Bolivia is also experiencing an outbreak of dengue fever and the Red Cross is working to address water and sanitation issues caused by the floods to curb the spread of the disease.
·          Assessments show that the most immediate needs of affected families are for relief items, rehabilitation of water and sanitation systems to prevent further spread of dengue and support for livelihoods as many crops have been lost.

Name: Philippines Typhoon Bopha-2012
Summary__c:
·         Typhoon Bopha made landfall on the eastern coast of Mindanao Island in the Philippines on December 4, 2012.
·         The storm caused flooding and landslides, destroying homes, agriculture and infrastructure across coastal areas.
·         Typhoon Bopha has affected 6.2 million people, killing 1,043 and leaving 841 missing. The storm damaged or destroyed over 130,000 houses and displaced over 986,000 people. 
·         Destruction of roads and bridges is hindering response efforts to the most affected areas.
·         Flooding and landslides have contaminated water supplies and 67 percent of health facilities in three provinces were damaged by the storm.

Name: Peru Floods-2012
Summary__c:
·          Hydro-meteorological disturbances and La Niña weather phenomenon have worsened Peru’s annual rainy season, causing major flooding across the country.
·          An estimated 650,000 people throughout Peru have been affected by the flooding and roads have sustained heavy damage, making relief distributions challenging.
·          On March 29, the government declared a state of emergency for three-quarters of Peru’s departments. In the most affected department of Loreto, more than 1,800 families have been evacuated to emergency shelters.
·          Initial needs assessments show that the most immediate needs of affected families include relief items, water and sanitation services, disease prevention efforts, and improvements to the conditions of emergency shelters.

Name: Philippines Floods-2012
Summary__c:
·         Following the heaviest rains recorded in three years, the Philippines has experienced severe flooding that has impacted 2 million people.  Floods have damaged more than 14,000 homes and displaced approximately 500,000 people.
·         The southwest monsoon was triggered by two storms, Typhoon Saola and Tropical Storm Haikui. More than 60 cities were immediately submerged in flood water.
·         Continuous rain has affected a large majority of the country and some flood water is not expected to recede until February 2013.
·         Thousands of people have sought refuge in evacuation centers, and are receiving basic provisions from the Philippine Red Cross.

Name: ARC - PRC - Yolanda Recovery Program, Leyte Province, Philippines
Summary__c:
The Philippines Red Cross (PRC) in partnership with the American Red Cross (ARC) is seeking USD 20 million to support a three year program beginning
July 2014 and ending by June 2017. Program implementation is the bulk of the budget with more than 75% allocated to the implementation of the core
sectors, Shelter & Settlements, Livelihoods and Sanitation. The budget includes a mandatory 6% overhead charge from PRC amounting to USD 1.2
million over the three years. This money is to support PRC operational needs not directly associated with implementation of the Leyte program,
including staffing at HQ (e.g. Recovery Task Force) among other costs. All PRC staff directly associated with implementation have been included in the
program budget while no ARC delegate or management costs are included in the program budget.

The PRC/ARC partnership (herein referred to as the Partnership) will implement an integrated program in accordance with the PRC Recovery Strategy
in the hardest hit province of Leyte targeting four municipalities (Tacloban City, Alangalang, Mayorga and MacArthur) and providing support in up to 25
Barangays.
 
The program uses the overall PRC Recovery Strategy goal: To contribute to building safe and resilient communities by identifying and addressing various factors
that will help people sustainably rebuild their lives, livelihoods and assets while ensuring that future climate, environmental and disaster related risks are addressed
and/or minimized.

Name: J/P HRO Rubble Removal and Demolition
External_Title__c: Rubble Removal and Demolition through J/P HRO
Staffing_Level__c: International Staff Present;Field Visits;Local ARC Staff, Regular Visits
Summary__c: One of the most immediate and pressing needs after the earthquake has been the clearance of millions of cubic meters of rubble and debris from streets, home sites and community buildings. J/P HRO has developed a rubble removal model that is innovative, reproducible and sustainable and which the International Organization of Migration (IOM) has identified as a hallmark of excellence in this field. While developing this expertise, J/P HRO has witnessed first-hand how rubble removal leads to the reinvigoration of local communities through improved safety and rebirth of businesses, schools, health centers and commerce. Furthermore, on-site construction training of local Haitians translates into future work in the construction trade, providing long-term employment in the communities, over the years of rebuilding to come.

Name: Uganda: Population Movement-2013
Summary__c:
·         The escalating violence in the Republic of South Sudan has provoked a mass population displacement within South Sudan and into neighboring countries. Uganda has taken the bulk of refugees who have continued to cross the borders since the beginning of the conflict in mid-December 2013.
·         More than 60,000 South Sudanese refugees have crossed into Uganda, and these numbers are expected to increase as the conflict continues between the Government of South Sudan and the opposition, despite the Peace Agreement signed by both parties in January 2014.
·         The increasing number of refugees means that tens of thousands of people in Uganda are in dire need of emergency medical care, shelter, food, water, and adequate sanitation facilities.

Name: Resilience in the Americas (RITA)
Summary__c: Every year in the Americas more and more people are living in conditions of vulnerability to natural hazards and climate change. To help reduce disaster risk and enhance community resilience in the region, the American Red Cross is working with Red Cross partners in the Bahamas, Belize, Colombia, Costa Rica, Ecuador, El Salvador, Guyana, Nicaragua, Panama and Peru to address local hazards and vulnerabilities in over100 disaster-prone communities. This initiative began with a Red Cross-led mapping and assessment process where communities themselves identified the most significant risks they face and the actions they can take to mitigate them. Some examples of community interventions include strengthening water and sanitation systems, delivering key messages about health promotion and disease prevention, and training and equipping community members with first aid skills and supplies. In addition to addressing specific hazards, another key program component is working with communities so they are able to self-organize and self-manage advocacy or education efforts that will help them be better prepared for future disasters.  The American Red Cross is also helping strengthen the capacity of Red Cross partners in the region to deliver services to communities. This program is being implemented in Bahamas, Belize, Colombia, Costa Rica, Ecuador, El Salvador, Guyana, Nicaragua, Panama and Peru, targeting more than 100 communities.

Name: Saving Lives in Caribbean (SLIC)
Summary__c: The ARC has been active in the Caribbean Region for a number of years working alongside Red Cross partners to implement resilience, health, and preparedness programs; risk reduction initiatives; and disaster response and recovery efforts. This project is a new initiative under way to introduce new technologies for communicating with the public about disaster risk in the Caribbean for preparedness, early warning, and response.  It aims to save lives and protect livelihoods and assets, increasing the impact of humanitarian efforts through low-cost means of reaching scale, and informing and empowering community decision-making on disaster management.  This 12-month regional initiative is funded by the United States Agency for International Development's Office of Foreign Disaster Assistance (OFDA).

Name: LAMIKA
External_Title__c: Lavi Miyò nan Katye Pa m  "A Better Life in my Neighborhood"
Staffing_Level__c: International Staff Present;Field Visits;Local ARC Staff, Regular Visits
Summary__c: Following the January 2010 earthquake, Haiti has experienced tremendous challenges in its recovery, especially in hilly and densely populated urban neighborhoods. In order to allow those affected by the earthquake to return to more secure homes, it is necessary to address their diverse needs more effectively and efficiently, through an integrated approach that encompasses land and housing, water and sanitation, health, disaster risk reduction and livelihoods interventions. Phase I of LAMIKA has focused on conducting participatory assessment and design activities in the target area of Campeche, a neighborhood in Carrefour Feuilles, Port au Prince. Over the next three years, the American Red Cross will implement LAMIKA with the goal of enhancing community and household resiliency while providing safer, healthier and more secure living conditions.  LAMIKA will contribute to a more hazard resistant Port au Prince and a better future for Haiti. LAMIKA will conduct activities in social empowerment, economic strengthening and physical renewal to address needs across sectors.  Likewise, activities will be designed to respond to needs at various scales, from the individual household to the municipal and national level.  The overall implementation strategy will be driven by a community-based, participatory approach. This project expects to reach an estimated 45,000 people with a range of services. The American Red Cross is coordinating with a number of government and humanitarian partners to achieve and expand this vision.

Name: Nepal CADRE
External_Title__c: Nepal - Developing/Strengthening Community-level Disaster Response Teams
Summary__c:
The American Red Cross (ARC) and Nepal Red Cross Society (NRCS), in recognition of the urgent need for local disaster responders throughout Nepal, are confident that extending the CADRE course, developed under the OFDA and ARC supported PEER program, to residents of disaster prone communities in eight districts will help to increase the effectiveness and timeliness of responses, thereby saving lives and assets.  

Nepal is one of the 20 most disaster-prone countries in the world.  In recognition of the urgent need for local disaster responders throughout Nepal, the American Red Cross and Nepal Red Cross are developing and training community-level disaster response teams to increase the effectiveness and timeliness of responses thereby saving lives and assets. The CADRE (Community Action for Disaster Response) course aims to enhance existing community response capacity by augmenting basic and moderate technical disaster management skills so communities can better cope with both mass casualty as well as smaller-scale disasters. The project is designed to focus on specific local hazards relevant to vulnerable communities and trainings address topics such as basic life support, micro-mitigation measures, community incident command systems, and light search and rescue. The program will identify and train 576 CADRE volunteers from 96 communities in eight districts of Nepal and indirectly benefits more than 40,000 people.

Name: Integrated Recovery Intervention in the Municipality of Tolosa, Philippines
External_Title__c: Integrated Recovery Intervention in the Municipality of Tolosa, Philippines
Summary__c:
The main objective of this project it is precisely to provide an integrated recovery response to the shelter, WASH and livelihoods needs of the residents of Tolosa affected by the Typhoon Yolanda, in order to strengthen and improve the existing conditions before the typhoon, and ensure the sustainability of them in the long term, thus fostering more resilient communities.
 
The multi sector process of recovery underlines the importance of complementing humanitarian life saving actions with the need to strengthen those processes, e.g., livelihoods, which are the foundations of longer term recovery and development.
 
The following recovery priority interventions seek to bridge the gap between immediate relief and longer term recovery and development through an integrated approach. This is a critical stage where humanitarian emergency relief for the majority of the affected population has come to an end but where long term reconstruction and rehabilitation has not started yet.
 
Following this approach, the project will start addressing the Community infrastructure and WASH rehabilitation to improve access to basic services as well as revitalize the local economy, and as an exit strategy after the WASH emergency operation ERU M15 deployment in Tolosa. The restoration of community infrastructure has the potential to bring all sectors of the affected communities together to work jointly for a common cause. Direct advantages to start of recovery intervention in this sector include: (i) resumption of community functions; (ii) re-establishment of a sense of routine or normalcy; and (iii) rebuilding of trust and confidence of the community in local leaders and Government.
 
The goal of recovery programming in community infrastructure is to restore community services, functions and processes, bringing them to normality. This provides the basement to build the recovery intervention in the other sectors of shelter and livelihoods.
 
The construction and shelter repair components of the program seek to maximise efficiency and promote synergies with the other components, such as Cash for Work (CfW) linked to shelter construction and WASH rehabilitation as a livelihoods protection intervention and provision of vocational trainings. Trained people as chainsaw operators, carpenters and other construction-related skills will be part of the building teams. The recovery interventions aim to capitalize on the emerging labour intensive livelihood opportunities related to reconstruction and rehabilitation.
 
Regarding livelihoods, short term interventions lasting 3-9 months will focus on: (i) grants and assets to resume pre-existent affected activities; (ii) Livelihoods entitlements information schemes; and (iii) cash for work linked to shelter and community infrastructures; while medium term interventions lasting 9-24 months will address: (i) skills training; (ii) Alternative income generation activities; and (iii) Organizational support for productive associations.

Name: IRC- Gender Based Violence Prevention
External_Title__c: Addressing Vulnerability of and Violence Against Women & Girls in Carrefour
Summary__c: The goal of this project is to reduce the incidence and mitigate the consequences of gender-based violence (GBV) in Port au Prince by addressing the needs of survivors and by empowering women and girls to participate more actively in Haitian society. This partnership project with the International Rescue Committee (IRC) will increase the capacity of local and community-based organizations that already provide valuable services, will conduct ongoing needs assessments and trainings with these organizations, and will develop an adolescent girls program. The program will also help to create financial opportunities for women and to promote women’s decision-making ability through empowerment and dialogue both within the home and community. IRC anticipates the project reaching approximately 9,090 women and girls directly in Carrefour-feuilles and in Champs de Mars camp.

Name: IRC: Latrine De-sludging
External_Title__c: WatSan Response through International Rescue Committee
Summary__c: The goal of this project is to reduce the public health risks, including cholera outbreaks, posed by un-maintained latrines and poor hygiene practices in temporary settlements of metropolitan Port au Prince, and also to facilitate local ownership of sanitation responsibilities.  De-sludging and latrine maintenance will be carried out in approximately 75 temporary settlements that are currently not being covered by other similar efforts. IRC anticipates the project reaching an estimated 90,000 people directly.

Name: Canadian Red Cross (CRC): Reconstruction of Jacmel Hospital
External_Title__c: Jacmel Hospital Partial Reconstruction through Canadian Red Cross
Summary__c: The American Red Cross is working with the Canadian Red Cross to improve access to health services in the South-East Department of Haiti by contributing 75%

Name: Ukraine: Civil Unrest-2013
Summary__c:
·         Demonstrations began in Kiev, Ukraine in November 2013 in protest of the government’s decision not to sign a trade agreement with the European Union. These demonstrations culminated in an unprecedented level of violence in Kiev in mid-February, after which the president vacated his post and an interim replacement government was approved by parliament.
·         Since the change in government, protests in opposition to the new government have emerged and escalated, primarily in southern and eastern Ukraine.
·         On March 16, 2014, the result of the referendum organized in Crimea around the question of independence from Ukraine was in favor of full independence of Crimea and integration into the Russian Federation. The results of the referendum and the subsequent integration of Crimea into the Russian Federation have not been recognized by any country, including Ukraine.
·         This situation in southern and eastern Ukraine continues to be volatile, with the possibility of further escalation of violence, and may lead to unpredictable consequences for the civilian population during its movement in search of safety. There is no reliable data on the actual number of people displaced.

Name: Indonesia Aceh Earthquake-2013
Summary__c:
·         A 6.2 magnitude earthquake hit Aceh province, Indonesia on July 2, 2013, affecting more than 52,000 people and damaging more than 16,500 houses.
·         The districts of Bener Meriah and Central Aceh sustained the most damage from the earthquake.
·         As of July 18, 2013, 42 deaths had been reported and a more than 2,500 people reported suffering injuries.
·         Access to the affected regions has been a challenge in the response operation, due to narrow roads and a risk of landslides. Many of the main roads in the affected area remain damaged or blocked by debris.
·         The earthquake damaged hospitals and schools and interrupted electricity and communication networks.

Name: Global Disaster Preparedness Center FY15
External_Title__c: GDPC FY15
Summary__c: The Global Disaster Preparedness Center is supporting priority preparedness aims of national societies to meet the needs of vulnerable communities by:  (1) enhancing information sharing and learning through the website and research; (2) providing opportunities for learning and technical assistance to at least 60 national societies; and (3) growing the disaster preparedness practitioner network to advance learning, dialogue and collaboration among national societies, academic and research institutions, nongovernmental organizations and other humanitarian actors.

Name: Zimbabwe Food Security-2013
Summary__c:
·         Zimbabwe is experiencing chronic and declining food security. Since March 2013 the number of people affected has increased 32 percent from 1.6 million to 2.2 million.
·         The late onset of rainfall followed by prolonged dry spells, coupled with households’ limited access to seeds for planting, has worsened the food security situation.
·         The government has started importing maize from South Africa and Zambia to guarantee food reserves in the country. Supply of grain is low throughout the country, with higher prices in rural areas.

Name: Disaster Project - Paraguay Drought-2013
Summary__c:
·         Drought conditions have impacted the Chaco region of Paraguay since early May, 2013. In September the Government of Paraguay declared a state of emergency in Chaco.
·         The drought is affecting an estimated 15,000 families in 246 communities.
·         Access to safe water is limited and crop, livestock and dairy production has decreased.
·         Some of the affected communities are still recovering from damaged infrastructure due to flooding last year.
·         Frost in July and August caused additional losses in agricultural production.
·         Assessments indicate an immediate need for food, clean water and repair of water catchments systems.

Name: Disaster Project - Philippines Typhoon Haiyan-2013
Summary__c:
• Typhoon Haiyan, locally known as Yolanda, made initial landfall in Eastern Samar, Philippines on November 8, 2013. The storm tracked across the Visayas region, bringing high winds, torrential rain and storm surge, impacting an estimated 16 million people.  
  • According to the latest Philippine government estimates, Typhoon Haiyan affected an estimated 16.1 million people, an increase from the previous estimate of 14.1 million. This includes 4.1 million people who remain displaced from their homes. 
  • Approximately 1.1 million houses were damaged during the typhoon.

Name: West Africa: Ebola Virus Outbreak-2014
Summary__c:
·         In March 2014, health authorities identified a rapidly evolving outbreak of Ebola in south-eastern Guinea. The disease has so far affected six of Guinea’s eight regions, including the capital, Conakry, as well as neighboring Liberia, Mali, Ghana and Sierra Leone. This is the first outbreak of Ebola in West Africa and the first time the disease has been found in a major city.
·         As of late May, the number of suspected Ebola cases in Guinea had increased to 281, including 185 deaths since the outbreak began in February. The last confirmed case of Ebola in Liberia was on April 6, with a total of 35 suspected cases, including six deaths. The number of related deaths in Guinea has slowed in the past month, however, because of the number of people still in the hospital suspected to be suffering from Ebola, the death toll could rise.

Name: Caribbean HIV AIDS Program (CHAP)
Summary__c:
The Caribbean HIV AIDS Program (CHAP) aims to contribute to the reduction of the incidence of HIV in Guyana, Jamaica and the Bahamas by addressing barriers to behavior change amongst MSM, SW, Miners and Youth at higher risk and create enabling environments for access to products and services. In line with American Red Cross (ARC) International Services Department Strategic Directions the next phase will aim to build stronger National Societies (NS) and more resilient communities that are better able to respond to health challenges with a focus on HIV. In the next year, FY13 the project will directly reach 14,999individuals from key populations at higher risk and indirectly 402,800 in the wider community with HIV prevention and stigma reduction interventions.
In July 2008 the International Federation’s Global Alliance on HIV was launched in the Americas. The Global Alliance on HIV provides a harmonized framework for scaling up national HIV programming with more than 60 NS world wide. Guyana and Jamaica are both members of the Global Alliance on HIV in the Caribbean and their HIV programming is implemented within this framework.
Since July 2010 ARC has been supporting the National Societies of Jamaica, Guyana and The Bahamas in a Caribbean HIV Prevention Project that is currently funded until June 2012. The high risk population groups are urban youth at higher risk in The Bahamas, young men who have sex with men (MSM) in Jamaica and Miners, Sex Workers and in and out of school youth in hinterland mining communities in Guyana.
As a new project working with these target groups in the three countries, the NS implementing the project have broken new ground in reaching most at risk populations (MARPs). Prior to this, most work in the Caribbean region focused on in school youth through the “Together We Can” (TWC) program. Evidence shows that there is increasing need to focus limited resources towards prevention activity with MARPs as these are the groups at highest risk of HIV infection. Teams within the NS have developed training material, outreach methodologies, skills in behavior change approaches, stigma reduction approaches and increased capacity in working on HIV projects. However in order to ensure a sustained and significant impact the work needs to continue within each of these countries.With an expanded period of funding, over a further three years, ARC will continue to work with these existing Caribbean countries, and will explore opportunities to expand into other high prevalence, high need countries in the region. The shift to a programmatic approach, begun in FY12, will continue into FY13 to FY15 with the Health Delegate relocating to Trinidad as part of a regional delegation. Increased focus will be on aligning activity under a Logic Model and utilizing Strategic Intervention Design with programming designed to reflect this focused approach. Behavior change approaches will be the underlying theme in all activity and the teams will continue to draw on lessons learned and regional sharing.
The Caribbean continues to be the region with the second highest HIV incidence rates across the world. While the Caribbean has witnessed significant achievements in the reduction of HIV incidence, efforts to continue to reduce HIV incidence in the region must focus on sustained long-term prevention strategies targeting MARPs. Continuing the Caribbean HIV prevention project in the region will not only enable NS to build their HIV programming expertise and establish themselves as key players in regional prevention efforts, but will also provide countries with the support needed to scale up HIV prevention efforts.
The program will address the gaps and needs of individuals with high-risk sex behaviors through: opportunities to increase knowledge, affect attitudes, and build skills through peer-education; counseling and testing; support groups for PLHIV; condom and lubricant distribution and referrals to local health services; and behavior change communication strategies using radio, social media and mass media campaigns as well as theater-based community wide events to raise awareness on a larger scale.
While the targeted groups have distinct characteristics that call for unique interventions, the interventions share common approaches and tools that have been adapted to reach different target groups or the same target groups in different cultural settings. As such, the program will continue to foster cross-country dialogue and the exchange of ideas, and encourage scale up and replication among project countries and within the region.
The regional delegation based in Trinidad will be developing a 2014 Operational Plan that includes the ARC International Services Department (ISD) 2014 Strategic Direction; Building Capable National Societies. As part of this, STAR (formerly called C-Bar) will be rolled out across the region with the three NS in CHAP being invited and supported to participate in the process. Within the CHAP Program, funds will be available to contribute to the NS based on the STAR assessments. In addition capacity development for NS project staff will include skills building around HIV technical, Monitoring and Evaluation (M & E) and management.

Name: Test-Devinder-Project
Summary__c: New Project

Name: HOPE - Cholera Prevention and Treament Efforts
External_Title__c: Cholera Prevention and Treatment Efforts through HOPE
Summary__c: The Red Cross has coordinated an aggressive response to the cholera outbreak that spread throughout Haiti and into areas of the Dominican Republic. As part of this response, the American Red Cross partnered with H.O.P.E. to operate a Cholera Treatment Center, a Cholera Treatment Unit and 19 Oral Rehydration Points. H.O.P.E. also trained community health workers, community volunteers and water and sanitation technicians to support their programming and educate people about cholera treatment and proper hygiene. This project reached an estimated 31,000 beneficiaries.

Name: Indonesia OD - Corporate Volunteers
External_Title__c: Indonesia Organizational Development - Corporate Volunteers
Staffing_Level__c: Local ARC Staff, Regular Visits;Local NS Staff, Regular Visits
Summary__c: The goal of this program is: To strengthen access and utilization of resources from the corporate sector to improve the operational and program performance of Indonesian Red Cross (Palang Merah Indonesia/ PMI). To implement the proposed PMI Corporate Volunteers Network Project, $400,000 is requested from the American Red Cross (ARC). These funds will be utilized to enhance the Indonesian Red Cross (PMI) capacity over a period of twenty four months (April 1, 2013 – March 31, 2015) via achieving the program goal related to a strengthened operational and program performance and through achieving the Strategic Objective (SO) in the technical area of improved volunteering, most specifically as recommended within the stated Declaration from the Global Volunteering Conference held in Budapest (15-17/9/2011) hosted by IFRC.

Name: Greater Jakarta Disaster Risk Reduction
External_Title__c: Greater Jakarta Disaster Risk Reduction
Summary__c:
The Greater Jakarta Urban Disaster Risk Reduction Project in Jakarta, Indonesia is a
thirty three month project (April 1, 2012- December 31 , 2014) designed to enhance
the Indonesia Red Cross (Palang Merah Indonesia - PMI) capacity on Disaster
Preparedness/Disaster Response (DP/DR), strengthen urban communities'
resilience to potential disaster risks and impacts posed by climate variability, climate
change and environmental degradation, and establish coordination and collaboration
between PMI and the government, academic and private sectors.
Climate-related disasters exacerbate a number of environmental and social
pressures in Indonesia and threaten the country's socio-economic development and
environment. In particular, increased flooding from sea level rise and challenging
climate risks exacerbate the health impacts of poor quality sanitation practices in
urban slum areas and elevate community risk to disaster .
The frequency and intensity of flooding due to changing climate risks will worsen an
already vulnerable situation if not addressed. Therefore, the intent of this project is to:
 
a. strengthen the capacity of PMI in technical and program management of
integrated urban Disaster Risk Reduction (DRR) and Climate Risk
Management (CRM) so that it is increased at its headquarters, chapter and
targeted branches;
 
b. establish coordination and collaboration between PMI, the government
(Dinas Kebersihan Kola-Sanitation Department), academic and private
sectors in implementing urban community based DRR, CRM, and Green and
Clean promotion;
 
c. increase the capacity of targeted communities in implementing ICBRR
approach to raise community knowledge, awareness, and best practices in
DRRJ CRM/ and Environmental Health;
 
d. thus leading to the goal to reduce deaths, injuries and socio-economic
impacts caused by climate-related disasters and environmental degradation
in Greater Jakarta by fostering more resilient communities and a stronger
PMI

The areas of Bogor, and south and north Jakarta have experienced flooding and/or
been inundated by sea tidal surges; heightened vulnerability persists due to regional
population growth in formal and informal settlements in low-lying areas.
ARC and PMI will select communities in Greater Jakarta for participation in this
program based on their vulnerability to climate risk and lack of resiliency. Although
this program will indirectly benefit approximately 3.5 million residents of the
Ciliwung River Basin area, direct beneficiaries will be selected from among the
four most vulnerable communities of each of three sub districts, within the 3 major
metropolitan JABODETABEK areas (i.e. Depok, North Jakarta and Bogor).
Project activities will take place in three targeted branches: PMI Bogor District,
Depok City and North Jakarta City.

Name: Indonesia Coastal Disaster Risk Reduction
External_Title__c: Indonesia Coastal Disaster Risk Reduction
Staffing_Level__c: Local ARC Staff, Regular Visits;Local NS Staff, Regular Visits
Sub_Sector__c: Contingency Planning;Education and Public Campaigns;First Responder Training;Micro-mitigation Projects;National Society Response Readiness;Capacity Building
Summary__c: The American Red Cross (ARC) proposes to work with affected coastal populations and assist the Indonesia Red Cross (Palang Merah Indonesia or PMI) to carry out Coastal Community Resilience and Disaster Risk Reduction activities.  Over a two year period, ARC, in collaboration with PMI, will assist up to 14 communities comprised of 90,456 direct beneficiaries and an overall coastal population of 1,839,191 indirect beneficiaries, all of whom are affected by a variety of recurring coastal disasters, to strengthen the resiliency of their communities in Aceh Jaya District in Aceh Province, Cilacap District in Central Java Province, and West Lombok District and Mataram City in West Nusa Tenggara Province.

Name: Myanmar Disaster Risk Reduction (OFDA)
Sub_Sector__c: Community-Based Disaster Preparedness;Education and Public Campaigns;First Responder Training;School Disaster Preparedness;Early Warning Early Action
Summary__c:
Myanmar is exposed to a plethora of natural hazards (i.e., cyclone, flood, drought,
earthquake, tsunami, and seasonal fire). In 2008, cyclone Nargis claimed 138,373
lives and affected an estimated 2.4 million people. The education sector was also
severely impacted, as the cyclone damaged or destroyed approximately 60% of the
total number of schools in the affected areas.
 
The American Red Cross (ARC), with financial assistance from OFDA, will support
the Myanmar Red Cross Society (MRCS) in implementing a new project entitled
"Enhancing Disaster Safety in Vulnerable Communities and Schools in Myanmar".
This project will allow MRCS to improve its institutional internal capacity and further
develop its emergency response capacity in communities and schools.

The purpose of this project is to reduce the number of deaths, injuries and impact
from disasters by increasing safety and resilience in Myanmar under two key
objectives: (1) to build the internal capacity of the MRCS (at national and branch
levels) to ensure the efficient delivery of disaster response and preparedness
programs, and (2) to reduce the vulnerability of Dedaye Township and Yangon
Downtown communities and schools by building MRCS's capacity to design and
conduct appropriate disaster risk reduction education.

Name: Bangladesh Tropical Cyclone-2013
Summary__c:
• On May 16, 2013 Cyclone Mahsen made landfall in southern Bangladesh and Myanmar.
  • Strong winds and flooding affected 1.5 million people in Bangladesh and killed 17.
  • Over 26,000 houses were destroyed and over 124,000 were damaged.
·         Over one million people were evacuated to cyclone shelters and, though most people have returned home, some remain in makeshift shelters or outside.
·         Currently, the greatest needs are for shelter, essential household items, clean water and food.

Name: Marshall Islands Drought-2013
Summary__c:
·         In May 2013 the government declared a state of disaster for 13 islands whose communities were severely affected by the drought and faced potential health, environmental, social and economic hardship.
·         The drought is reported to be affecting 6,400 people across 15 islands north of the capital Majuro.
·         The most significant operational challenge continues to be logistics. Many locations can only be reached by boat, which can involve several days travel and is highly dependent upon weather conditions.
·         Due to the lack of availability and high cost of transport by boat and aircraft, these communities depend upon locally grown crops, which have been badly damaged by the drought, creating the threat of serious food shortages.

Name: Vietnam Typhoon Wutip-2013
Summary__c:
·         On September 30, 2013, Typhoon Wutip made landfall in Vietnam as a Category 1 typhoon bringing strong winds, heavy rains and flooding. With sustained winds of 72 miles per hour, experts say Typhoon Wutip is the strongest storm to strike Vietnam since 2006.
·         The storm damaged homes, health centers, schools and power lines and caused losses in crops and livestock in six central provinces of Vietnam. Specifically, some 374 houses collapsed, more than 212,000 houses were damaged and more than 43,000 houses were submerged.
·         Over 119,000 people have been affected, including 11 dead and 214 injured.
·         This storm was followed by Typhoon Nari on October 15, which also made landfall in Vietnam as a Category 1 storm, affecting the coastal provinces and the central highlands. Nine people were killed and more than 120,000 evacuated.

Name: Philippines Central Visayas Earthquake-2013
Summary__c:
·         On the morning of October 15, 2013, a magnitude 7.2 earthquake struck the Central Visayas region of the Philippines. The quake was the strongest to hit the area in more than 20 years.
·         The earthquake left 222 people dead and 976 injured. It damaged more than 78,000 houses, at least 11,500 of which were destroyed.
·         The quake caused extensive damage to public health facilities and schools, as well as electric power failures and disruptions, which interrupted water supply.
·         Markets in the most impacted cities have started to function, although not at the same scale as prior to the quake. Authorities have now repaired many damaged bridges and roads.

Name: Philippines Typhoons and Floods-2013
Summary__c:
·         Starting on August 8, 2013, Typhoon Utor hit Manila and surrounding Philippines provinces, causing 11 deaths and damaging 11,000 homes. A week later, monsoon rains fuelled by Tropical Storm Trami (locally named Maring) flooded the same region. The rains caused major damage to houses, roads and infrastructure. Flooding affected 3 million people over five regions and killed 27.
·         In the final months of 2013, an additional nine storms impacted the previously-affected areas. Some of the affected provinces have been hit repeatedly by the series of storms, leaving a total of five million people affected and at least 126,000 houses damaged.
·         In addition to the damage to household items, livelihoods and shelters, the severe tropical storms brought health concerns. In all, the severe weather events that have occurred since August 2013 left at least 6,200 people dead and damaged more than a million houses across the country.

Name: Namibia Drought-2013
Summary__c:
·         Namibia is suffering from severe drought conditions after one of the driest rainy seasons in decades.  The lack of available water is causing a strain on local farmers resulting in food shortage and loss of livestock.
·         The Government of Namibia issued a national state of emergency in May 2013, seeking international assistance for the estimated 331,000 people in rural communities affected by the drought.
·         An inter-agency emergency assessment lead by the Namibian Directorate of Disaster Risk Management indicates that agricultural production will be very poor as a result of the below average rainfall. 
·         Cases of cholera and malnutrition are increasing, likely due to the shortage of safe water sources and poor sanitation and hygiene practices.

Name: PiH - Operational Support for University Hospital
External_Title__c: Partners in Health Operational Support for University Hospital
Summary__c: The American Red Cross partnered with Partners in Health to provide operational support to University Hospital, the largest general hospital in Port au Prince, which serves a population of 500,000 people. The American Red Cross helped pay staff salaries and also underwrote the establishment of an Intensive Care Unit in partnership with the Haitian Ministry of Health.

Name: UN Foundation - Coordinated Vaccination Campaign - Round 1
Summary__c: The densely populated camps of Port au Prince present a serious public health challenge, particularly for children and other vulnerable residents.  The American Red Cross helped to fund a vaccination campaign that reached nearly 1 million people in more than 700 settlements soon after the earthquake.  Depending on age, patients received a combination of vaccinations against diphtheria, tetanus, pertussis, measles, and/or rubella. Children were also given vitamin A supplements to boost immunity and worm infection treatment.

Name: QAF - Sandy Restocking of Relief Supplies (ARC DI)
Summary__c: QAF Response following Hurricane Sandy - implemented by ARC with HRC and IFRC support

Name: ARC - Post-Earthquake Health and Hygiene Promotion in Camps (PEHP)
Summary__c: The American Red Cross Post-Earthquake Health Promotion Program followed a community-based approach to providing first aid and promoting hygiene, health and safety in the camps. Program activities included hygiene promotion, condom distribution, and education on preventing cholera, malaria, HIV, and sexual and gender-based violence.  The program also conducted disease mitigation activities in the camps.  In most cases, this program worked in the same locations as the Emergency Disaster Risk Reduction program, complementing disaster risk reduction work with health and hygiene promotion services to camp communities.

Name: Project Medishare - Operational Support for Bernard Mevs Hospital
Summary__c: The American Red Cross has supported the payment of operating expenses, payroll and administrative fees for the Bernard Mevs Hospital Project Medishare Critical Care Trauma and Rehabilitation Program in Port au Prince. The hospital operates 24/7 for the general public, providing the only critical care and trauma services for all of Haiti. The Hospital Bernard Mevs Project Medishare employs 190 staff members.

Name: HOPE - Mobile Health Clinic in Borgne
Summary__c: This project aimed to improve the health of women and children in the rural commune of Borgne, Haiti, by providing 12 mobile health clinics as part of the comprehensive cholera prevention and response initiative of a Haitian organization, Haiti Outreach Pwoje Espwa (H.O.P.E), that is supported by the American Red Cross.

Name: WFP - Emergency Food
External_Title__c: World Food Program Emergency Food
Summary__c: Vulnerable groups in Haiti have long been dependent on food assistance, and this need has only increased since the earthquake. The American Red Cross provided food rations for over 1 million people, primarily young mothers and children, through a partnership with the UN World Food Programme.  The American Red Cross also donated nearly 3 million packaged meals for distribution in the early days of the response.

Name: Together We Can: HIV Prevention
Summary__c: Together We Can provided interactive HIV prevention messaging and skills-building to more than one million youth in three countries—Guyana, Haiti and Tanzania. The goal of the program was to educate youth to strengthen life skills, improve decision-making and encourage safer behavior. The program targeted young people between the ages of 10-24 years with a special emphasis on hard-to-reach and vulnerable groups like out-of-school youth and girls. In addition to distributing free condoms, the program utilized traditional classroom environments as well as non-traditional learning methods such as peer-to-peer advising, community events and entertainment-information sessions. It was a pre-earthquake program that was implemented in areas that were not directly affected by the earthquake.  The Together We Can program reached more than 550,000 youth in Haiti.

Name: Cholera Prevention and Treatment Program (Cholera Program)
UN Foundation - Coordinated Vaccination Campaign - Round 2
Summary__c: This is a resumption of the multi-agency “Coordinated Vaccination Campaign” to maintain the elimination status of measles, rubella and polio in Haiti.

Name: ARC - Cholera Prevention in Camps and Communities
Summary__c: The Red Cross has coordinated an aggressive response to the cholera outbreak that has spread throughout Haiti and into areas of the Dominican Republic.  The American Red Cross is working to stem the spread of the disease as well as provide care for those infected by it. As part of this effort, the American Red Cross trained staff and volunteers to go out into camps and communities across the country to provide cholera and hygiene education. The teams also distribute soap, oral rehydration solution and water purification tablets.  This project has also set up Oral Rehydration Points and Posts, where trained volunteers can refer cholera patients that they encounter to proper treatment facilities. This program built upon similar work that the American Red Cross has been doing in Port-au-Prince since the start of the outbreak in October 2010, while expanding its reach to parts of Haiti’s North.

Name: QAF - Miron Relocation Support
Summary__c: QAF: From an request from the Government of Haiti, the project aimed to relocate IDP families situated in a dangerous ravine through a rental subsidy program. A total of 103 families were relocated in December, 2011.

Name: ARC - Blood Products for Hospitals
Summary__c: The American Red Cross coordinated the shipment of over 5,300 units of blood to support the Haiti earthquake response.  The American Red Cross provided nearly 4,300 of the blood units; the remaining blood was provided by America’s Blood Center, the Blood Centers of America and the National Blood Exchange. Each unit of blood contained 450 ml, or roughly one pint of blood. Most of this blood went to the Pan American Health Organization, although American Red Cross blood units were also sent to the UN Mission in Haiti as well as to a US Naval Hospital in Cuba that treated patients evacuated from Haiti.

Name: USAID - Sustainable and Responsive Housing and Urban Development Program
External_Title__c: Dynamic Community Development and Urban Reconstruction Program with USAID
Summary__c:
The Sustainable and Responsive Urban Development Program is subdivided into four related Components, which will target two zones in the West Department of Haiti: Canaan and Tapis Rouge.
 
Canaan was the site of an emergency relocation camp site (known as Corail) for internally displaced persons. Following the construction of Corail, permanent settlements began to develop in the area without any planning on land use, building construction, or any support for the development of basic social or infrastructure services. According to UN-Habitat, Canaan presently has the country’s greatest concentration of new housing construction, with a mix of income groups constituting the new community.
 
Tapis Rouge is the site of a former IDP camp in Carrefour Feuilles that was emptied by the government of Haiti in 2013. The site is of strategic importance due to its central location and site conditions. It is located adjacent to the densely populated informal settlements of Carrefour Feuilles and near to existing infrastructure and service provisions. It is a gently sloping site with comparatively minimal exposure to natural hazard. 
 
To address these issues, the program will work in these two areas to provide urban planning, infrastructure improvements, and livelihood opportunities.

Name: Enzigma Test Disaster-2014
Summary__c: Enzigma Test Disaster

Name: Community Health and Malaria Prevention in Northeastern Haiti
Summary__c: Haiti has the highest infant and maternal mortality rates in the Western Hemisphere, which has often partially been attributed to the threats of malaria and insufficient diet. The American Red Cross had been working in Haiti since before the earthquake to reduce these deaths and continued to do so after the earthquake struck through activities such as distributing insecticide-treated mosquito netting to pregnant women and families with children, educating households on malaria prevention, and guiding communities to improve their environments and manage their water and sanitation facilities. Communities also designed mitigation projects, such as building latrines, to directly improve local hygiene standards. This was a pre-earthquake program that was implemented in areas that were not directly affected by the earthquake.

Name: Burundi: Population Movement-2012
Summary__c:
§  During the past decade over 525,000 Burundian refugees have voluntarily returned home, while more than 94,000 still remain in neighboring countries, including Tanzania.
§  In 2011, the Tanzanian Government informed its partners that it would close one of its refugee camps by the end of 2012 and repatriate all the Burundian refugees living in that camp.
§  Many of the returnees have experienced been in exile for twenty years. A considerable percentage of the returnees have never lived in Burundi, complicating an already difficult situation.
§  Challenges faced by returnees include redistributed land, shifts in social or commercial systems and changes to social networks. Refugees who have been dependent on humanitarian aid for many years in the refugee camps will now need to find work and support their families in an unfamiliar environment.
§  During the process of repatriation, some families have also been separated and need help to reconnect.

Name: HRC - Institutional Change and Development Program (OD MOU)
External_Title__c: Haitian Red Cross Institutional Development Allocation

Name: PrevSIDA + HHAP
External_Title__c: HIV Prevention to Youth and High Risk Populations
Summary__c: In a continuation of the HIV prevention work we have been doing in Haiti since 2004, the American Red Cross, in partnership with the Haitian Red Cross and Population Services International, has joined a consortium of NGO’s funded by USAID working to prevent the sexual transmission of HIV in Haiti. The project will work to identify populations and settings with high-risk behavior and then to improve HIV/AIDS- related knowledge, attitudes, skills and behaviors of the most at-risk populations through individual outreach and community-wide events. The project will also work to strategically link communication and education interventions for sexual prevention of HIV with other health related services and commodities, including targeted condom promotion and availability, as well as livelihoods initiatives for most-at-risk populations and those in settings characterized by high risk behaviors. The project seeks to reach 1,062,680 individuals from high risk youth and adult populations over the course of four and a half years.

Name: FY15 Zimbabwe Urban Disaster Risk Reduction (DRR)
Summary__c: ARC intends to enter into a one year PA with the Zimbabwe Red Cross Society (ZRCS) beginning July 1, 2014 regarding the Zimbabwe UDRR project.  The proposal is still being finalized, however the project will focus on two neighborhoods (Dzivarasekwa and Hatcliffe) in Harare and has two primary objectives: 1) increasing the capacity of ZRCS to deliver, coordinate, and advocate for urban disaster risk management; AND 2) strengthen the resilience of urban communities through the implementation of community based disaster risk reduction and livelihood security interventions

Name: FY15 Building Resilient African Communities (BRACES) in Zambia
Summary__c:
Building Resilient African Communities (BRACES) is a multi-year program designed to increase the resilience of communities to withstand the shocks and stresses of annual floods in the Zambezi River basin. This project complements and supports the on-going Zambezi River Basin Initiative activities implemented by Zambia Red Cross Society with support from IFRC working in the flood-affected areas of the Zambezi River Basin.
 
Working closely with the Zambia Red Cross Society, the primary objective of this project is to reduce the number of deaths, injuries and socioeconomic impacts caused by disasters through strengthening the Zambia Red Cross Society (ZRCS) and building safer and more resilient communities in the Sesheke and Kazungula districts. It specifically focuses on building the capacity existing community structures such as the Satellite Disaster Management Committees and the Branch Executive Committees to implement Disaster Risk Reduction activities in the flood prone areas of Kazungula and Sesheke for the most vulnerable populations.

Name: FY15 Building Resilient African Communities (BRACES) in Namibia
Summary__c:
Building Resilient African Communities (BRACES) is a multi-year program designed to increase the resilience of communities to withstand the shocks and stresses of annual floods in the Zambezi River basin. This project will complement and support the on-going Zambezi River Basin Initiative activities implemented by Namibia Red Cross Society with support from IFRC working in the flood-affected areas of the Zambezi River Basin. The Namibia Red Cross Society (NRCS) requests $75 000 from the American Red Cross (ARC) in support of the continuation of the BRACES project implemented for two phases in Namibia from October 1, 2011 to June 30, 2014. This third phase will cover the period July 1, 2014 to June 30, 2015.
 
Working closely with the Namibia Red Cross Society, the primary objective of this project is to reduce the number of deaths, injuries and socioeconomic impacts caused by disasters through strengthening the NRCS and building safer and more resilient communities in four rural communities in the Zambezi Region of Namibia: Lisikili, Mbalansinte, Schukmansburg (Luhonono) and Imukusi. All four communities experience annual flooding affecting food production, livestock management and water sources in addition to destroying houses, damaging assets and general infrastructure.

Name: FY15 Building Resilient African Communities (BRACES) in Zimbabwe
Summary__c:
Building Resilient African Communities (BRACES) is a multi-year program – currently in Phase III in Zimbabwe - designed to increase the resilience of communities to withstand the shocks and stresses of annual floods in the Zambezi River basin. This project complements and supports the on-going Zambezi River Basin Initiative activities implemented by Zimbabwe Red Cross Society and the IFRC.
 
Working closely with the Zimbabwe Red Cross Society, the primary objective of this project is to reduce the number of deaths, injuries and socioeconomic impacts caused by disasters through strengthening the Zimbabwe Red Cross Society (ZRCS) and building safer and more resilient communities in four Administrative Wards: Siachilaba, Simatelele, Manjolo and a new ward (as yet determined) in Binga District, Zimbabwe.
 
Previous humanitarian interventions during disasters in Binga district focused on response activities with little involvement of communities. Phase I and II of the BRACES project looked at equipping communities with more awareness on disaster risk reduction initiatives which they can implement in their own communities thus bringing about safer and more resilient communities. The third phase of the project continues to address this imbalance through implementing more long term interventions that will build a culture of risk awareness and mitigation among communities whilst more knowledge will be imparted in a new area of focus.

Name: FY15 Nyaruguru Resilience Project in Rwanda
Summary__c:
The project seeks to reduce the number of deaths, injuries and socio economic impacts caused by disasters through strengthening Rwandan Red Cross Society and building safer and more resilient communities in Nyaruguru district of Rwanda.
 
After the American and Rwanda Red Cross societies formalized their partnership in mid-2013, they jointly conducted a community needs assessment in Nyaruguru district that identified several key challenges facing the district, including general poor health and sanitation, contributing to preventable diseases and poor hygiene practices; environmental degradation due to charcoal burning and reliance on wood fuel; and disaster risks related to landslides and drought. The quality of healthcare is generally low, but improving. Another challenge is limited household incomes largely linked to very few formal employment options and limited micro-enterprise opportunities.
 
Given the diversity of priority needs expressed by the Nyaruguru communities, the Nyaruguru Resilience project will employ integrated programming as the technical approach. This approach aligns with the Rwanda Red Cross society’s “Model Village” program, which the Rwanda Red Cross has implemented across more than one hundred communities. The selected programming approach also aligns with American Red Cross guidance for programming for resilience.
 
During FY15 the project will target 6 villages (2 each in Busanze, Cyahinda and Nyagisozi Sectors), while also completing initial assessment allowing for expansion into additional 6 villages, in FY16 (bringing total project coverage to 12 Villages by the start of year two).

Name: BPRM Emergency Assistance to Congolese & Burundian Refugees in Tanzania
Summary__c: The Emergency Assistance to Congolese Refugees project has been funded by BPRM since 2004.  Activities are designed around two objectives that provide critical support to the overall Refugee Relief Operation: (1) maintain and improve the quality of basic health services for at least 90% of refugees in Nyarugusu camp and 10% of the host community population by providing in-patient and out-patient curative, preventative, and rehabilitative healthcare and community outreach/health promotion; and (2) ensure the healthy repatriation of refugees returning to their country of origin from TRCS-managed camps by conducting cross-border fact finding missions and providing health and referral information to returning refugees.

Name: FY15 Tanzania Integrated HIV and AIDS
Summary__c:
This is an integrated HIV and AIDS prevention, care, and support project in Tanzania that started in May 2009 which is being extended an additional year with ARCT funding. 
 
The goal of the project is threefold, namely to decrease the incidence of HIV, to reduce HIV/AIDS associated morbidity and mortality and to improve the quality of life of the chronically ill (including people living with HIV (PLHIV) and orphans and vulnerable children (OVC) in the Geita district of Tanzania.  The four objectives comprise support to the chronically ill, support to OVC, improving HIV related knowledge, attitudes and skills and strengthening the capacity of the Tanzania Red Cross Society (TRCS) in HIV/AIDS programming.

Name: FY15 Building Community Resilience in Tanzania
Summary__c: The goal of the community resilience project in Tanzania is to achieve “Well organized, safer and healthier communities with capacities to manage health risks and disaster in Geita Region in Tanzania.”  The Geita Region, which houses the two proposed project sites - Bukombe and Mbogwe districts – is situated to the northwestern part of Tanzania. The American Red Cross has developed the community led integrated programming for resilience (CLIPR) assessment process to guide the development a community resilience  approach to programming. Findings of the pilot CLIPR assessment conducted in Geita Region of Tanzania between October and November 2013, noted many vulnerabilities. Over a three year period this project will target a total of 24 communities; for FY15, the project will be implemented in 11 communities (villages) within Bukombe and Mbogwe Districts in Geita Region of Tanzania.

Name: Solomon Islands: Floods-2014
Summary__c: Prolonged heavy rainfall associated with a tropical depression, which later became Tropical Cyclone Ita, passing over the Solomon Islands on April 3, 2014 resulted in severe flooding in the capital, Honiara, and associated damage in Guadalcanal, Makira, Malaita and Isabel provinces. River systems across the northwest, central and north of the island flooded, destroying homes, damaging bridges, blocking roads, and displacing families. A total of 21 people are confirmed dead, 25 missing and an estimated 52,000 people affected across the Solomon Islands, around half of which are children (approx. 10 percent of population).

Name: Balkans: Floods-2014
Summary__c: Serbia and Bosnia and Herzegovina (BiH) have been affected by cyclone Tamara experiencing extremely heavy rain, strong winds and low temperatures. On 13 May, continuous, heavy rainfall began, and the region recorded three months’ worth of rain in three days. It is the worst rainfall recorded in BiH since 1894. In BiH, more than 40% of the country is under water. It is estimated 1,000,000 have been affected by floods and landslides in Bosnia and more than 1.6 million is Serbia.
